# BunGo (Bundler 4 Go) - Framework Rules and Context

## 1. Project Motivation & Philosophy
BunGo is a lightweight, high-performance idiomatic Go web framework and asset bundler. It allows developers to write Go server logic and React (JSX) views in the same repository, seamlessly binding them together without Node.js, npm, or complex external build pipelines.

## 2. AI Agent Directive (CRITICAL)
**All AI agents working on this project MUST continuously keep this `.cursorrules` file updated with the most up-to-date, comprehensive understanding of the framework's architecture, conventions, and guidelines. If you introduce a structural change, a new standard, or modify a core behaviour, you must update this file immediately to reflect it.**

**In addition to updating `.cursorrules`, ALL AI agents MUST continuously keep the `README.md` file up to date with the most recent usage patterns, features, and examples to serve as an accurate, comprehensive guide for developers using this framework.**

**Whenever changes are made to how the library works or its features, AI agents MUST also automatically update the relevant documentation files inside the `docs/` directory. This is critical for preserving developer documentation structures.**

**Testing and regressions:** Keep existing `*_test.go` files aligned with the rest of the codebase (patterns, package layout, naming, and assertions that document intended behaviour). **Whenever you introduce or change framework behaviour, run the full test suite before finishing:** from the repository root run `go test ./...`, then run `go test ./...` inside `engine/aws` and `engine/gcp` (separate Go modules, not covered by the root `./...`). Fix failing tests or update tests in the **same** change set as the code—do not leave main broken or tests stale.
## 3. Core Architectural Boundaries (CRITICAL)
* **Embedded Bundling & React:** BunGo embeds `esbuild` directly via its Go API (`github.com/evanw/esbuild/pkg/api`). Furthermore, BunGo **embeds React and React-DOM directly into the Go binary** using `//go:embed` inside `internal/builder/vendor/`. An esbuild plugin (in `internal/builder/react_plugin.go`) intercepts `import "react"`, `import "react-dom"` / `react-dom/client`, and `import "bungo/render"`. The virtual module `bungo/render` exports `_bungoRender(Component, elementId?)` and `useBungoData()` so views can mount their root component and read page handler data without importing helpers from `react-dom/client` or touching `window.__BUNGO_DATA__` directly; when `elementId` is omitted it defaults to `"root"`. BunGo supports local view entry files in `.jsx`, `.tsx`, `.js`, and `.ts`. BunGo also supports Deno-style remote URL imports in JSX/TSX (for example `https://esm.sh/...`) through `internal/builder/remote_import_plugin.go`, which resolves and fetches remote ESM modules (including relative imports between remote modules) at build time. Remote modules that reference React/ReactDOM URL variants are normalized back to BunGo's embedded React runtime to prevent duplicate React instances and hook/context crashes. The React JSX automatic runtime shim preserves `key` semantics (third `jsx` argument), so keyed lists reconcile correctly and keys are not rendered as child text. The compiler uses esbuild's `Inject: ["bungo/render"]` so `_bungoRender` / `useBungoData` are auto-injected and view files do not need to import them.
* **Theme / locale:** User-facing CLI strings, dev TUI copy, and scaffold error messages default to English in `internal/theme/en.go` (`theme.EN`). Shared constants (`EmbeddedReactVersion`, `ScaffoldGoVersion`, `CLIVersionUnknown`, plus build-time identifiers `BunGoModuleImportPath` and `BunGoNewServerSelector`) live in `internal/theme/versions.go`. The root package re-exports `EmbeddedReactVersion` for API stability.
* **CLI (`cmd/bungo`) & Build/Dev Workflows:** BunGo ships a Cobra-based helper command at `cmd/bungo`. `bungo init <project-name>` scaffolds a runnable showcase project (Go server, routes, templates, and React view) and includes remote `https://...` import usage in the generated view to demonstrate full embedded bundling functionality. Passing `--typescript` generates a `.tsx` showcase view and `tsconfig.json`. `bungo dev` (CLI in `cmd/bungo`, implementation in `internal/dev`) runs `go run <entry>` from project root (`--entry`, default `"."`), starts a websocket endpoint at `/__bungo` on fixed port 35729 (`bungo.DevWebSocketPort`), uses `fsnotify` (recursive dir watches with ignore rules) to detect source/template/view changes, debounces burst events before reload, disconnects websocket clients, restarts the app process, and enables browser auto-refresh on reconnect. The framework detects dev mode via `BUNGO_DEV_ENABLED=1` and injects a small reconnect client script (same port) into rendered pages. **`bungo build` is specified in section 6 below** (implementation in `internal/build`).
* **Shared path helpers:** Common slash/path normalization and project-relative validation logic is centralized in `internal/fileutil` and reused by build discovery/resolution and runtime asset storage paths. Avoid duplicating ad-hoc `TrimSpace` + slash conversion + clean/escape checks in multiple packages.
* **No Node.js / NPM:** Never generate `package.json`, `node_modules`, or npm commands.
* **No Business Logic:** The framework is strictly infrastructure. It routes requests, applies security layers, compiles JSX, and renders templates. It must NEVER import database drivers or user-specific models.
* **Fail-Fast Asset Validation + Storage Abstraction:** The server strictly requires the provided `webDir` and its `layouts/` and `views/` subdirectories to exist at boot. Validation and file reads go through `AssetStorage`, which attempts embedded memory first and falls back to disk, then `panic()` when required assets are missing. This same abstraction is used by server validation, rendering, builder compilation, and static file serving.
* **Template vs Layout:** `Template` is always required—the page-specific `.gohtml` file in `layouts/`. `Layout` is optional and enables Go template composition: a wrapper template (e.g., `base.gohtml`) defines `{{block "content" .}}`; the Template fills it with `{{define "content"}}...{{end}}`, avoiding repeated `<html><head><body>` boilerplate. `Server.DefaultLayout` sets a global layout for all pages that do not specify their own.
* **Automated Template Injection:** `RenderTemplate` injects `window.__BUNGO_DATA__` and the compiled JSX bundle automatically. Default behavior inlines the compiled bundle with `<script type="module">`. When `Server.SetAssetOptimization(true)` is enabled, BunGo injects `<script type="module" src="/_bungo/<view>.js">` and serves cacheable bundle files from `/_bungo/...`. When no Layout is used: scripts go before `</head>` or `</body>`. When a Layout is used: scripts are injected into the layout. Developers must NOT manually place these script tags in their views.
* **Agnostic Handlers & Rendering:** 
  - Page Handler signature: `func(req *bungo.Request) (map[string]any, error)`
  - API Handler signature: `func(req *bungo.Request) (bungo.APIResponse, error)`
  - The internal `RenderTemplate` returns formatted HTML entirely agnostic of the Server environment. Adapters (e.g., `HTTPEngine`) are responsible for passing this to an `http.ResponseWriter` or corresponding vendor boundary.
* **Configuration Structs / Reference Passing:** Prefer pass-by-reference for internal/library-facing function inputs wherever possible so internal flows keep identity and avoid unnecessary copies. **Exception:** developer-facing public APIs can stay pass-by-value when that keeps DX simpler (for example route registration structs in top-level server APIs). When changing a signature from value to pointer, all consumers, examples, and docs must be updated in the same task.
* **Security layers:** Routes may list `SecurityLayer` names on `PageRoute` or `ApiRoute`. Layers run in order; if any handler returns `false`, the adapter responds with **HTTP 401 Unauthorized** and does not run the page/API handler (see `engine/http.go` and `engine/aws/aws.go`).
* **Static assets:** `engine.HTTPEngine` and `engine_aws.LambdaEngine` serve `GET /static/...` directly from `AssetStorage` (memory-first, disk-fallback) when `<webDir>/static` exists. Static routes bypass BunGo Security layers.

## 4. Core Terminology
* **`Server`**: The central registry. Holds routing maps, security layers, and delegates listening to the `Engine`.
* **`Engine`**: An interface (`Invoker`) representing the execution environment. Translates incoming events (e.g., standard `net/http` or AWS Lambda) into a generic `bungo.Request`. Available engines: `engine.NewHTTPEngine()` (net/http), `engine.NewHTTPSEngine(certFile, keyFile)` (net/http TLS via `http.ListenAndServeTLS`), `engine_aws.NewLambdaEngine()` (AWS Lambda HTTP API v2 / Function URL), `engine_gcp.NewGCPEngine(name)` (Google Cloud Functions).
* **`Request`**: Framework-agnostic HTTP request representation containing Headers, GET/POST Params, Body (raw bytes or parsed interface), and an `Internal` map for passing context (like JWT claims) between Security Layers and Handlers.
* **`APIResponse`**: Contains an HTTP `StatusCode` (int) and a `Body` (any) to be marshaled to JSON.
* **`Template`**: The required page-specific `.gohtml` file in `layouts/`. Defines page content, optionally with `{{define "content"}}` when using Layout composition.
* **`Layout`**: Optional wrapper template in `layouts/` that defines `{{block "content" .}}`. Used for composition to avoid repeating `<html><head><body>` in every template.

## 5. Function Comment Standard (CRITICAL)
* Every function and method must use a standardized doc comment format.
* Comment must start with the exact function/method name.
* Required structure:
  1. One concise sentence describing behavior.
  2. `Inputs:` section with one bullet per parameter.
  3. `Outputs:` section with one bullet per return value. If no returns, use `- none`.
* Keep comments implementation-agnostic and focused on contract (what it does, not line-by-line internals).
* When function signatures are changed (especially value -> pointer updates), update all consumers and documentation examples in the same task.

## 6. `bungo build` pipeline (CRITICAL for maintainers and AI agents)
This section documents the exact contract between user app code, the CLI build, and runtime embedding. **If you change server bootstrap syntax, import paths, discovery heuristics, or generated code, update the relevant `internal/build/*.go` files, `internal/theme/versions.go` (when constants apply), this section, and `docs/cli-tools.md` / `docs/deployment.md` in the same task.**

### End-to-end sequence (`internal/build.Run` + helpers in `internal/build/*.go`)
1. Read the app module path from `go.mod` (`readModulePath`).
2. Resolve the build entry with `go list` (`resolveEntryPackage`): entry must be package `main`.
3. Resolve output path: default `./bin/<name>` or `--output` (`resolveOutputPath`). For file entry targets (for example `cmd/server/main.go`), default output uses the file stem (`main`) rather than `main.go`.
4. Resolve web asset roots:
   - when `--web-dir` is supplied, validate/normalize that path with `resolveManualWebDir` and skip auto-discovery;
   - otherwise run auto-discovery with `discoverServerWebDirs` (see “Discovery contract” below).
5. Create a **temporary** directory under the project root (`bungo_embed_gen_*`), copy each resolved web tree into it preserving relative paths (`generateEmbeddedAssetsPackage` + `fileutil.CopyFSTreeToDir`).
6. Emit `embed_assets_gen.go` in that package: `//go:embed <dirs...>`, `var embeddedAssets embed.FS`, `init()` calling `bungo.RegisterEmbeddedAssetsFS(embeddedAssets)`. The import path for the root BunGo module must come from **`theme.BunGoModuleImportPath`** (not a hardcoded string in multiple places).
7. Write a **temporary** blank import in the **entry package** (`bungo_embed_import_gen.go`) so the generated package is linked and `init()` runs (`generateEntryImportFile`).
8. Normalize file entries (`--entry <path>.go`) to their containing package target, then run `go build -o <output> <package-target>` (`normalizeBuildEntryTarget` + `runGoBuild`).
9. Deferred cleanup removes the temp embed package and the temp import file (generated sources must never remain in the tree after a successful build).

### Discovery contract (what `bungo build` recognizes today)
Discovery runs only when `--web-dir` is not supplied.
**Pre-filter (fast path):** Discovery is scoped to the resolved **entry package directory** (and its subdirectories). For each `.go` file in that scope, the file is skipped unless its raw source contains **both** substrings **`theme.BunGoModuleImportPath`** and **`theme.BunGoNewServerSelector`** (see `internal/theme/versions.go`). This avoids parsing unrelated packages and reduces false positives.

**AST match:** After parse, collect **call expressions** where:
- `Fun` is `*ast.SelectorExpr` with `Sel.Name == "NewServer"` (any receiver type — typically `bungo.NewServer` or a named import).
- Second argument `Args[1]` is a `*ast.BasicLit` **string literal** (not a variable or `const` reference).

**Normalization:** The string is validated/normalized by `normalizeWebDirForEmbedding` into (a) an **embed alias path** based on the literal (e.g. `./web` -> `web`) and (b) a **source directory** resolved from the **project root / command working directory** used by `bungo build` (not from the declaring Go file path). Source must remain inside repo root (`..` escape rejected). This keeps build embedding aligned with `go run` / `bungo dev` runtime expectations.

**Fallback:** If nothing matched, embed **`web`** from the entry package directory when `<entryDir>/web` exists; otherwise fall back to project root `./web` if present.

**Validation:** For discovered entries, `generateEmbeddedAssetsPackage` now fails fast when a resolved source directory is missing or not a directory, instead of silently skipping it. This prevents accidentally shipping binaries with an empty embedded asset filesystem.

**Implications for API design:** If `NewServer` gains a different name, different argument position, or non-literal `webDir`, **discovery must be updated** or users must adopt a documented pattern. If users import BunGo under a custom module path (replace directives), the **pre-filter substring** may need adjustment alongside AST logic.

### Manual web roots (`--web-dir`)
- `bungo build --web-dir <path>` manually specifies a single web root to embed.
- Presence of `--web-dir` disables auto-discovery, so only the manual root is embedded.
- Relative `--web-dir` values are resolved from project root and embedded under the same normalized relative path (for example `./cmd/site/web` -> `cmd/site/web`).
- Absolute `--web-dir` values are allowed only when they resolve inside project root; embedding outside repo root is rejected.

### Runtime wiring
Embedded assets are registered via `RegisterEmbeddedAssetsFS` in `embedded_assets.go`. `AssetStorage` in `asset_storage.go` reads **embedded FS first**, then disk under `WebDir`, so production binaries stay portable without changing app code.

## 7. Logging & Error Messaging Standard
* **Uniform Formatting:** Any framework-level panics, formatted errors, or internal informational logs MUST follow the uniform namespaced format `BunGo <Category> <Level>: <Message>`.
* **Categories:** Use clear module/feature descriptors corresponding to the failure area: `Startup`, `Routing`, `Security`, `HTTPS`, `GCPEngine`, `Builder`, etc.
* **Levels:** Use `Error`, `Info`, or `Warning`.
* **Examples:**
  - `panic("BunGo Routing Error: ApiRoute.Method is required")`
  - `log.Printf("BunGo Security Error: Security Layer '%s' was requested but is not registered.", layerName)`
  - `log.Printf("BunGo GCPEngine Info: Starting GCP Functions Framework on port %s", port)`
* **Rationale:** By standardizing this prefix throughout the framework, developers using BunGo can immediately identify and filter when an issue originates from missing framework configurations or built-in safeguards rather than their own application code.